                <listAnnotation xml:lang="en" type="typednotes">
                    
                    	<note xml:id="n_transcrSource" type="transcrSource">
                    	    
<p>Original manuscript</p>
                    	</note>
                    
                    
                    	<note xml:id="n_dating" type="dating">
                    	    
      <p>On the verso of the sketch <hi rend="italics">Starry night over the Rhône</hi> (<rs type="artwork" ref="artwork.xml#_192">F - / JH 1594</rs>), enclosed with <ref target="let693.xml">letter 693</ref> to Eugène Boch, appears this crossed-out, unsent fragment of a letter written by Van Gogh to Gauguin. This fragment was thus the beginning of a letter, and although the text continued, it was lost when a piece of the paper was cut off.</p>     
<p>Because the text is to be found on the sketch enclosed with <ref target="let693.xml">letter 693</ref> of 2 October 1888 and is an answer to <ref target="let688.xml">letter 688</ref>, written about 26 September 1888, this fragment probably dates from September-October 1888.</p>
                    	</note>
                    
                    
                    
                    	<note xml:id="n_remarks" type="remarks">
                    	    
                                    
<p>Jansen <hi rend="italics">et al</hi>. 2000. The version of the text published there differs in certain details from the present text.</p>
                                    
                                
                    	</note>
                    
                </listAnnotation>
                <listAnnotation xml:lang="en" type="ogtnotes">
                    
                </listAnnotation>
                <listAnnotation xml:lang="en" type="notes">
                    
                        <note n="1" xml:id="note-t-1">
                            

<p>This is probably a response to a remark made by <rs type="person" ref="bio.xml#_1039">Gauguin</rs> in his letter to Van Gogh of about 26 September 1888 (<ref target="let688.xml">688</ref>): ‘I’m fearful that your brother, who likes my talent, rates it too highly. If he found a collector or speculator who was tempted by <hi rend="italics">low prices</hi>, let him do it. I’m a man of sacrifices, and I’d like him to understand that whatever he does, I’ll find it well done.’ Referring to this passage, Van Gogh wrote in his next letter to Theo: ‘Now I have a letter from Gauguin, who seems very sad ... I’ll send you his letter with the reply’ (<ref target="let691.xml">691</ref>). Evidently the crossed-out text is a discarded version of that reply; we do not know the letter that Van Gogh actually sent to Gauguin.</p>
                        </note>
                        
                    
                        <note n="2" xml:id="note-t-2">
                            

<p>The three no. 30 canvases depicting the park are <hi rend="italics">The public garden (‘The poet’s garden’) </hi>(<rs type="artwork" ref="artwork.xml#ill_2713">F 468 / JH 1578</rs>), <hi rend="italics">Path in the public garden</hi> (<rs type="artwork" ref="artwork.xml#ill_2716">F 470 / JH 1582</rs>) and an unknown painting, previously described as ‘a round cedar or cypress bush’ (<ref target="let689.xml">689</ref>) and shortly thereafter as ‘the garden with the round bush and the oleanders’ (<ref target="let694.xml">694</ref>).</p>
                        </note>
                        
                    
                        <note n="3" xml:id="note-t-3">
                            

<p>
      <hi rend="italics">Ploughed fields (‘The furrows’) </hi>(<rs type="artwork" ref="artwork.xml#ill_2719">F 574 / JH 1586</rs>).</p>
                        </note>
                        
                    
                        <note n="4" xml:id="note-t-4">
                            

<p>
      <hi rend="italics">Starry night over the Rhône </hi>(<rs type="artwork" ref="artwork.xml#ill_2723">F 474 / JH 1592</rs>). Not all of the line is on the page. Only the accents and the tops of the ascenders of the uncertain reading ‘la nuit étoilée’ can be seen, but this reading is supported by <ref target="let691.xml">letter 691</ref>.</p>
                        </note>
                        
                            

                        
                    
